04042nam a22004935i 9780773562226DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735622267 a10.1515/97807735622262doi  a(DE-B1597)657708  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD849bM436 1990eb 7aPOL0240002bisacsh04a338.911 aPratt, Cranford, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMiddle Power Internationalism :bThe North-South Dimension /cCranford Pratt. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tMiddle Power Internationalism and Global Poverty -- tInternational Reform and the Like-Minded Countries in the North-South Dialogue 1975-1985 -- tTowards North-South Middle Power Coalitions -- tTechnological Revolution and the Restructuring of Trade Production: Some Implications for the Western Middle Powers and the Newly Industrializing Countries -- tHas Middle Power Internationalism a Future? -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the 1970s the picture looked very different. The countries involved in the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development gave the impression that they felt it their duty to help the Third World. Since the beginning of the 1980s, however, this attitude has disappeared from the foreign policy agenda of one developed country after another. It seems that only when a state's self-interest is at risk does a concern for humanistic values emerge. Canada, Denmark, the Netherlands, Norway, and Sweden -- the key middle powers -- have long been regarded as significantly more responsive to the needs of the Third World than most of the other rich industrialized nations. Middle Power Internationalism helps to identify the scope and limitations of the foreign policies of these middle power countries with respect to what Cranford Pratt terms "humane internationalism." Asbjrn Lvbraek describes the major effort in the 1970s to mobilize middle power support for the New International Economic Order. Bernard Wood considers the prospects for effective co-operation between the middle powers of the North and the South. And Raphael Kaplinsky studies the likely impact of new technologies and new methods of production on the economies, and consequently on the North-South policies, of the industrial middle powers. Cranford Pratt concludes with a reflective essay in which he discusses the constraints upon middle power internationalism and the future of middle power diplomacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aKaplinsky, Raphael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLøvbrÆk, Asbjørn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt, Cranford, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWood, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356222640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562226423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562226/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles